WEBVTT

1
00:00.450 --> 00:09.000
- Welcome back to "Understanding Quantum
Information and Computation." My name is John Watrous, and I'm the Technical Director
for IBM Quantum Education.

2
00:09.000 --> 00:16.650
This is the fifth lesson of the series, and it's the first lesson in
the second unit of the series, which is on Quantum Algorithms.

3
00:16.650 --> 00:23.550
In this unit, we'll investigate
computational advantages of quantum information, that is, we'll take a
look at what we can do

4
00:23.550 --> 00:31.650
with quantum computers and the advantages that quantum computers might potentially have
over classical computers.

5
00:31.650 --> 00:37.680
We're gonna be focusing on what we can do with a single quantum computer as opposed to a distributed
setting, for instance,

6
00:37.680 --> 00:42.000
where multiple quantum computers interact over a network of some sort.

7
00:42.000 --> 00:48.750
There are, in fact, quantum advantages to be found in distributed settings, where communication and
cryptography come into play,

8
00:48.750 --> 00:51.930
but we're not going to be
talking about those things in this unit.

9
00:51.930 --> 00:57.690
This unit is about quantum algorithms running on single quantum computers.

10
00:57.690 --> 01:04.620
Let's start with a natural question. What advantages might a quantum
computer potentially offer?

11
01:04.620 --> 01:10.500
The main one is that quantum computers might provide faster solutions to some computational problems.

12
01:10.500 --> 01:16.560
Time is precious, and although the computers we
use every day are pretty fast, they're still way too slow

13
01:16.560 --> 01:22.830
to solve certain computational problems just because of the inherent
computational difficulty of those problems.

14
01:22.830 --> 01:29.310
This potential that quantum computers might allow us to solve problems that classical computers
are too slow to solve

15
01:29.310 --> 01:35.220
is really what's driven
quantum algorithms research for the past few decades.

16
01:35.220 --> 01:43.050
There are other computational
resources besides time that can be considered, like the amount of computer memory required for computations,

17
01:43.050 --> 01:50.670
but quantum computers can't
offer too much savings in terms of memory, as it turns out, and classical computer
memory is pretty inexpensive

18
01:50.670 --> 01:57.240
particularly compared with quantum memory. So there just isn't
very much promise here.

19
01:57.240 --> 02:03.900
We could also think about other resources like the amount of energy
needed for computation, but you don't actually
need much energy at all

20
02:03.900 --> 02:08.100
to compute classically, particularly if you're
willing to slow things down.

21
02:08.100 --> 02:13.260
So it really is the time
required for computations, that's our main focus.

22
02:13.260 --> 02:20.010
Here's an overview for the lesson, which is about a specific
model of computation known as the query model.

23
02:20.010 --> 02:27.930
You can think of this model as being kind of like a Petri dish for developing algorithmic ideas, both quantum and classical.

24
02:27.930 --> 02:34.290
It's not meant to be a practical model that describes the sorts
of computational problems we encounter in real life.

25
02:34.290 --> 02:42.390
We'll move away from the query model in subsequent lessons of this unit and focus instead on models motivated by more practical
notions of computation,

26
02:42.390 --> 02:45.900
but the query model is a
very good place to start.

27
02:45.900 --> 02:52.860
It's a simple model that allows us to explore the
potential of quantum computers without a lot of technical
details getting in the way,

28
02:52.860 --> 02:59.220
and it also allows us to isolate some of the
really important ideas behind quantum computing and how it works.

29
02:59.220 --> 03:07.440
Quantum computing did, in fact, first develop within this model, and the ideas that were
developed within it very directly inspired
important quantum algorithms

30
03:07.440 --> 03:12.180
such as Shor's algorithm for factoring.

31
03:12.180 --> 03:18.390
In the first section of the lesson, we'll take a look at specifically what the query model of computation is,

32
03:18.390 --> 03:25.497
and in the second, third,
and fourth sections, we'll discuss three
quantum query algorithms, namely Deutsch's algorithm,

33
03:25.497 --> 03:31.560
the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm,
and Simon's algorithm, which reveal increasingly
impressive advantages

34
03:31.560 --> 03:37.830
of quantum computers
over classical computers within the query model of computation.

35
03:37.830 --> 03:45.720
To explain the query model of computation, let's first begin with a more standard
abstraction of computation.

36
03:45.720 --> 03:51.630
Here's a picture that
represents a computation in very simple and basic terms.

37
03:51.630 --> 03:59.250
We have an input, which usually takes the
form of a binary string, although we could use other
symbols if we wanted to.

38
03:59.250 --> 04:05.280
The input is provided to the computation, which is represented by a blue
rectangle in this picture,

39
04:05.280 --> 04:14.700
and the result of the computation is that some output is produced, and again, that's most
typically a binary string.

40
04:14.700 --> 04:19.680
Of course, this picture
is not at all specific about how the computation itself works.

41
04:19.680 --> 04:25.800
We can formulate different
specific computational models to do that, such as Turing machines
and Boolean circuit,

42
04:25.800 --> 04:30.600
or quantum circuits if we're thinking about
quantum computation.

43
04:30.600 --> 04:38.940
It's true that this picture
doesn't represent the fact that many of the
computers we use every day are continuously receiving
input and producing output,

44
04:38.940 --> 04:44.970
essentially interacting with us and with other computers through
the internet, for instance.

45
04:44.970 --> 04:48.450
But we're not trying to represent
those interactions here.

46
04:48.450 --> 04:53.910
This is about modeling
isolated computational tasks.

47
04:53.910 --> 05:00.180
For example, the input might be the
binary encoding of a number or a representation of a matrix

48
05:00.180 --> 05:06.210
or a description of a molecule or really anything else we have in mind, and there's some computational task

49
05:06.210 --> 05:10.830
being performed on that input alone.

50
05:10.830 --> 05:19.560
The key point here is
that the entire input is provided to the computation, and nothing about the
input is hidden from it.

51
05:19.560 --> 05:23.970
The query model of
computation works differently.

52
05:23.970 --> 05:31.620
In the query model, the input is made available
in the form of a function which the computation can
access by making queries,

53
05:31.620 --> 05:36.690
or in other words, by evaluating the function
on different inputs.

54
05:36.690 --> 05:40.320
Here you can see that represented
in the form of a picture.

55
05:40.320 --> 05:46.830
Similar to what we had before, the computation is represented
by a blue rectangle, but instead of receiving an input directly

56
05:46.830 --> 05:55.980
in the form of a string
of bits, for instance, it accesses the input by effectively asking questions
and receiving answers.

57
05:55.980 --> 06:03.330
We sometimes use the
terms oracle and black box to refer to the mechanism
that provides the input.

58
06:03.330 --> 06:11.910
There is a distinction between
an oracle and a black box in complexity theory, but that won't be relevant at all for the purposes of this discussion.

59
06:11.910 --> 06:16.950
Anyway, these terms are meant
to convey the basic idea.

60
06:16.950 --> 06:24.630
In ancient Greece, you
could go to an oracle, like the Oracle at Delphi,
and ask an important question,

61
06:24.630 --> 06:33.000
and the oracle would answer
that specific question, but she certainly wouldn't tell you everything that she knew.

62
06:33.000 --> 06:39.420
Along similar lines, when
we think about a black box, we have in mind some
sort of process or system

63
06:39.420 --> 06:47.340
where we can choose what goes in and we can see what comes out, but we don't have any understanding
of its inner workings.

64
06:47.340 --> 06:56.010
And that's the case here. The input to the problem
takes the form of a function, and all that we can do is
to evaluate that function,

65
06:56.010 --> 07:01.080
but otherwise, we don't have
any knowledge or understanding of how it works.

66
07:01.080 --> 07:07.650
Throughout the lesson,
we'll reserve the letter f for the function that
represents the input, and we'll make the assumption

67
07:07.650 --> 07:11.550
that it always takes the
form that you see right here.

68
07:11.550 --> 07:17.850
Sigma denotes the binary alphabet, so f is a function from strings
of bits to strings of bits,

69
07:17.850 --> 07:26.100
and specifically, we'll
assume that the input to f is a string of bits having length n, and the output is a string
of bits having length m,

70
07:26.100 --> 07:30.150
where n and m are positive integers.

71
07:30.150 --> 07:39.480
For different problems, we'll
have restrictions on n and m, but in all cases, the input function will
take a form like this.

72
07:39.480 --> 07:47.700
When we say that a
computation makes a query, what we mean is that the
function f is evaluated once,

73
07:47.700 --> 07:55.590
that is, some string x of length N is selected by the computation, and the string f of x is
then made available to it

74
07:55.590 --> 08:02.220
by the oracle or the black box. And finally, the very simple way that we'll measure the computational cost

75
08:02.220 --> 08:06.630
of a query algorithm is to count how many queries it requires.

76
08:06.630 --> 08:13.290
So, although it is true that
we are really most interested in how long computations take, when we study the query model,

77
08:13.290 --> 08:20.190
we generally keep things
simple and just count queries, and that's what we will do in this lesson.

78
08:20.190 --> 08:26.850
Now, let's take a look at a
few examples of query problems, meaning computational
problems in the query model,

79
08:26.850 --> 08:35.910
and here, by the way, I'm just gonna describe
the problems themselves, and at this point, I won't say anything
about how to solve them.

80
08:35.910 --> 08:39.420
The first problem is the OR problem.

81
08:39.420 --> 08:46.110
In this case, the input is a function
from n bits to just 1 bit, so m is equal to 1 for this problem,

82
08:46.110 --> 08:50.640
and the required output for
the problem is either 1 or 0.

83
08:50.640 --> 08:57.570
If there is some n bits string x for which f of x is equal to 1, then the correct answer is 1,

84
08:57.570 --> 09:04.470
and otherwise, if f of x is
always 0 for every string x, then the correct answer is 0.

85
09:04.470 --> 09:12.690
So if we think about the function f as providing us with random
access to two to the n bits, one for each n bit string x,

86
09:12.690 --> 09:20.760
then what the it's asking
for is the OR of those bits, and that's why it's called the OR problem.

87
09:20.760 --> 09:27.360
Another example is the parity problem, which is similar to the OR problem except that asks for the parity,

88
09:27.360 --> 09:34.470
or in other words, the eXclusive OR of all of the single-bit
output values of the function.

89
09:34.470 --> 09:43.260
Another way to say that is
that the correct answer is 0 if the number of n bits strings x for which f of x is equal to 1 is even,

90
09:43.260 --> 09:48.570
and the correct answer is
1 if that number is odd.

91
09:48.570 --> 09:54.390
An example of a problem where m is not necessarily equal to 1 is the minimum problem.

92
09:54.390 --> 10:00.840
Here, the function f takes the usual form, and there are no restrictions on n and m,

93
10:00.840 --> 10:07.680
and the correct answer is whatever output value
of the function comes first in the lexicographic
or dictionary ordering

94
10:07.680 --> 10:16.680
of binary strings. Alternatively, if you wanna
think about strings of length m as representing non-negative
integers in binary notation,

95
10:16.680 --> 10:25.080
then the correct answer
is the smallest possible or minimum value that
comes out of this function.

96
10:25.080 --> 10:33.090
Sometimes we also consider query problems where we have a promise
on the input function, or in other words, some
sort of guarantee on it,

97
10:33.090 --> 10:38.070
and we don't worry about functions that don't meet that promise.

98
10:38.070 --> 10:42.870
Functions that don't satisfy the promise are considered as "don't care" inputs.

99
10:42.870 --> 10:50.040
And we're just not responsible for what happens on those inputs.

100
10:50.040 --> 10:54.840
Here's an example of a query problem with a promise called unique search.

101
10:54.840 --> 10:58.020
It's related to the OR
problem, but it's different.

102
10:58.020 --> 11:04.110
The input function has the same
form as for the OR problem, which is that it takes
n bits strings to bits.

103
11:04.110 --> 11:10.200
This time, we're promised that
there's exactly one string Z that causes f to evaluate to 1,

104
11:10.200 --> 11:18.000
with f of x being equal to 0
for every string x besides z, and the correct output
is this unique string z.

105
11:18.000 --> 11:25.350
Of course, there are
choices for the function f that don't satisfy this condition, but we don't place any requirements at all

106
11:25.350 --> 11:29.460
on algorithms for this problem when they're given such
functions as input.

107
11:29.460 --> 11:35.700
We only care about the functions that do satisfy the promise.

108
11:35.700 --> 11:42.270
Now, all four of the
problems I just mentioned are pretty natural problems, meaning that it's easy to explain them,

109
11:42.270 --> 11:51.240
and it's easy to imagine situations in which a need to solve them might arise, but some query problems
aren't like this at all.

110
11:51.240 --> 12:00.210
In fact, sometimes, we consider highly
contrived query problems, where it's difficult to imagine that anyone would ever
actually wanna solve them.

111
12:00.210 --> 12:06.210
Simon's problem, which we'll
see later in the lesson, kind of falls into this category, but there are some other ones

112
12:06.210 --> 12:15.840
that are much worse in some sense, but they, nevertheless, actually turn out to be pretty important to the study of the query model.

113
12:15.840 --> 12:21.060
We don't study these problems because we necessarily want
to solve them in practice.

114
12:21.060 --> 12:27.630
The way you can think about it is that we are looking for
extremes of various sorts,

115
12:27.630 --> 12:35.070
in particular, when we're working within
this Petri dish of a model, a natural way to explore
quantum algorithmic ideas

116
12:35.070 --> 12:42.090
is to formulate highly-contrived problems, where we can best exploit the
power of quantum computers.

117
12:42.090 --> 12:50.190
And this can actually
shed a great deal of light on how quantum computers
can potentially be useful in more practical settings.

118
12:50.190 --> 12:57.630
We can formalize the notion
of a query in different ways depending on what computational
model we're working with.

119
12:57.630 --> 13:04.680
For example, in the Turing
machine model of computation, which we haven't talked about and we won't get into in this series,

120
13:04.680 --> 13:12.570
there's a certain way of
formalizing the notion of a query that makes sense for that model.

121
13:12.570 --> 13:22.800
For circuit models, we define special types of
gates called query gates, and that's how queries
are formally represented.

122
13:22.800 --> 13:29.040
For Boolean circuits, there's a very simple way of doing this, which is simply to imagine
that we have query gates

123
13:29.040 --> 13:35.130
that evaluate the input function directly, like you can see here on the screen.

124
13:35.130 --> 13:41.910
The idea is that we can
use these query gates to build circuits that solve whatever
problem we're looking at,

125
13:41.910 --> 13:48.570
and in order to work correctly, the circuits have to give the right answer for whatever input function f is given,

126
13:48.570 --> 13:55.170
assuming that it meets the promise in the case of a promise problem.

127
13:55.170 --> 14:01.260
Here's a simple example
of a Boolean circuit that solves the parity
problem when n is equal to 1,

128
14:01.260 --> 14:06.150
so the input function f is from
1 bit to 1 bit in this case.

129
14:06.150 --> 14:15.510
What this circuit does is to evaluate the function
f on the inputs 0 and 1 using these two query gates.

130
14:15.510 --> 14:22.740
It then plugs the two output values it
gets from the query gates into the Boolean circuit from lesson three that computes the XOR,

131
14:22.740 --> 14:25.970
which is the same thing as the parity.

132
14:25.970 --> 14:33.240
To be clear, these two
input values right here are not inputs into the problem,
meaning the parity problem,

133
14:33.240 --> 14:41.460
when we're working with the query model, the input to the problem
is the function f, and you should think about these
two inputs into the circuit

134
14:41.460 --> 14:47.730
as being hard-coded
values that never change, they're essentially part of the algorithm.

135
14:47.730 --> 14:53.910
We want to compute the XOR of f 0 and f 1, so we initialized these
two wires in this way

136
14:53.910 --> 15:00.510
to make it work. We've used two query gates
here, this one and this one,

137
15:00.510 --> 15:08.400
and so the algorithm represented
by this Boolean circuit makes two queries, and if we think about the
parity problem for a moment

138
15:08.400 --> 15:15.780
for functions from one bit to one bit, we see that it's absolutely necessary for any Boolean circuit
that solves this problem

139
15:15.780 --> 15:19.200
to make at least two queries.

140
15:19.200 --> 15:26.130
If you only make one query so that you only know one
output value of the function f and not the other, you don't actually have
any information at all

141
15:26.130 --> 15:33.060
about the parity, because the other output value
could equally well be 0 or 1, leading to either of the
two possible solutions

142
15:33.060 --> 15:40.080
to the problem. So in terms of the number
of queries that it makes, this Boolean circuit is as good as it gets

143
15:40.080 --> 15:45.630
for the parity problem
when n is equal to 1.

144
15:45.630 --> 15:52.920
There's one other point about query gates that's worth mentioning before we move on, and that is that when we're designing and analyzing query algorithms,

145
15:52.920 --> 15:57.930
we don't worry at all about how
query gates are implemented.

146
15:57.930 --> 16:04.650
It's assumed that these
query gates are given to us, and the difficulty of building
them isn't our concern.

147
16:04.650 --> 16:12.690
You can think of the
query gates themselves as being the input if you like, and it's not our job to create the input, we're just trying to
solve a particular problem

148
16:12.690 --> 16:20.280
given the input. Of course, when f is a function
from one bit to one bit, there are only four possible choices,

149
16:20.280 --> 16:27.210
and it would be easy enough
to implement any one of them, but in general, for functions
with many input bits,

150
16:27.210 --> 16:32.520
it could be extremely difficult to implement query gates
for those functions.

151
16:32.520 --> 16:39.210
To be clear, this isn't
to say that the issue of how query gates are
implemented isn't important, but rather that it isn't considered

152
16:39.210 --> 16:43.350
to be part of the cost
of a query algorithm.

153
16:43.350 --> 16:50.490
This is consistent with the idea that this isn't really
about practical computing or actually building circuits per se,

154
16:50.490 --> 16:57.570
it's about working within
a theoretical framework that tells us interesting
things about computation.

155
16:57.570 --> 17:05.370
We will have more to say about this when we make the jump from this model to a more standard model of computation, and that's mainly what the next lesson,

156
17:05.370 --> 17:11.430
Lesson 6, will be about.

157
17:11.430 --> 17:15.030
Now let's turn our attention
to quantum circuits.

158
17:15.030 --> 17:21.060
For quantum circuits, we're going to change the
definition of query gates to make them unitary.

159
17:21.060 --> 17:27.630
We want to be able to make
queries within quantum circuits and for them to operate
linearly on quantum states

160
17:27.630 --> 17:32.550
so that we can effectively
make queries in super position.

161
17:32.550 --> 17:40.230
It might seem like we're moving
the goalposts, so to speak, by changing what we mean by a query in comparison to what we just
saw for Boolean circuits,

162
17:40.230 --> 17:44.850
but there is justification for it that we'll discuss in more
detail in the next lesson.

163
17:44.850 --> 17:48.930
For now, it's just a definition.

164
17:48.930 --> 17:56.280
Specifically, the
definition is as follows, given any function f of
the same form as before,

165
17:56.280 --> 18:03.990
meaning that it maps n bits
strings to m bits strings, the query gate Uf acts on n + m qubits

166
18:03.990 --> 18:09.570
and is defined by the
action described here on standard basis states.

167
18:09.570 --> 18:16.500
We'll see a figure
representing this definition in just a moment, but first, let me make clear the notation
that's being used here,

168
18:16.500 --> 18:23.070
and that is whenever we
use the symbol for the XOR as an operation between two
strings of the same length,

169
18:23.070 --> 18:30.360
we're referring to the
bitwise eXclusive OR, and here you can see an example.

170
18:30.360 --> 18:39.570
In the definition, we have that both y and f of
x are strings of length m, so this string right here
represents the string we get

171
18:39.570 --> 18:48.420
by XORing those two strings
together, one bit at a time, and here's the diagram
explaining how these gates work.

172
18:48.420 --> 18:52.530
The top n qubits correspond to
the argument of the function.

173
18:52.530 --> 19:00.660
And when they start out
in a standard basis state, cat x in this diagram, that standard basis state
goes through unchanged

174
19:00.660 --> 19:03.960
and gets echoed as part of the output.

175
19:03.960 --> 19:10.560
The bottom m qubits correspond to the output
of the function f, and when they start out in
any standard basis state,

176
19:10.560 --> 19:19.560
cat y in this diagram, what happens is that the
output of the function f of x gets XORed onto the string y.

177
19:19.560 --> 19:30.750
This is what happens for
standard basis states, and if we wanna know
what happens in general for other quantum states, we
use linearity, as we always do.

178
19:30.750 --> 19:37.620
A reason to define query gates like this where we echo the input and we use the bitwise XOR for the output

179
19:37.620 --> 19:43.710
is that these gates are always unitary for any choice of the function f.

180
19:43.710 --> 19:46.830
This is, in fact, a
deterministic operation.

181
19:46.830 --> 19:53.160
And if we were to express it as a matrix for any choice of a function F, we'd get a permutation matrix,

182
19:53.160 --> 19:59.340
meaning one with a single one in each row and in each column, and all other entries equal to 0.

183
19:59.340 --> 20:03.780
And permutation matrices
are always unitary.

184
20:03.780 --> 20:14.160
In fact, for this operation, we'll get that the operation
is its own inverse, so Uf dager equals Uf.

185
20:14.160 --> 20:20.160
If all we wanna do with these
gates is to evaluate f of x for some string x, that's easy,

186
20:20.160 --> 20:28.680
we can just set y to
be the all-zero string. So when we take the bit y's eXclusive OR, we end up with just f of x.

187
20:28.680 --> 20:34.200
Here, by the way, you can see the notation that's used to denote the all-zero string.

188
20:34.200 --> 20:37.800
It looks like 0 to the power M, but that's not what it means.

189
20:37.800 --> 20:42.150
It means the string of zeros
having length equal to M.

190
20:42.150 --> 20:50.250
When we're talking about
strings as opposed to numbers, exponents typically mean that we repeat that string
some number of times,

191
20:50.250 --> 20:54.330
so this is 0 repeated m times.

192
20:54.330 --> 20:59.160
It's just a convenient and precise way of describing this string.

193
20:59.160 --> 21:06.180
Once again, when we're
working with the query model, we aren't worrying about how
to implement these query gates.

194
21:06.180 --> 21:11.310
That's the same issue
we had with query gates for Boolean circuit.

195
21:11.310 --> 21:19.950
It's not our job to prepare the input, we're given the input in the
form of these query gates.

196
21:19.950 --> 21:28.230
I will point out though, that if we know how to
implement the function f using a Boolean circuit, then it is possible to
translate that implementation

197
21:28.230 --> 21:37.890
pretty directly to a quantum
circuit implementation of Uf, and we'll see exactly how
that works in the next lesson.

198
21:37.890 --> 21:47.460
As an aside, it is quite straightforward to create a Boolean circuit
that operates like this, using a single classical
query gate for the function f,

199
21:47.460 --> 21:53.490
but that is quite different from having a quantum
circuit implementation of this unitary gate.

200
21:53.490 --> 22:00.300
The point, however, is that
for classical query algorithms, having a query gate that works like this is, in fact, equivalent

201
22:00.300 --> 22:07.470
to having an ordinary
classical query gate for f, in the sense that either one can be implemented using the other.

202
22:07.470 --> 22:16.200
In this section of the lesson, we'll discuss Deutsch's algorithm, which is a very simple
quantum query algorithm, but it really is a gem.

203
22:16.200 --> 22:26.820
This algorithm comes from a 1985 paper written by David Deutsch, was one of the very first people to work on the theoretical
foundations of quantum computing.

204
22:26.820 --> 22:32.903
The algorithm itself represents a very small part
of Deutsch's 1985 paper, and in fact,

205
22:32.903 --> 22:38.940
the algorithm we now
call Deutsch's algorithm is actually an improved version of the algorithm that Deutsch described.

206
22:38.940 --> 22:46.320
It provides a very modest example of how quantum computers can
offer computational advantages, but you have to start somewhere,

207
22:46.320 --> 22:50.820
and it really was an important spark that got things started.

208
22:50.820 --> 22:57.660
Deutsch's algorithm solves a query problem that's often called Deutsch's problem in the context of quantum computing,

209
22:57.660 --> 23:07.860
but in fact, it's none other
than the parity problem for functions from one bit to one bit, which we've already talked about.

210
23:07.860 --> 23:16.920
As we've already seen, there are four functions
from one bit to one bit, and they're described here on the screen by their tables of values.

211
23:16.920 --> 23:24.450
The first and last of these
functions are constant, while the middle two are balanced in the sense that the two
possible output values

212
23:24.450 --> 23:28.080
appear the same number of times.

213
23:28.080 --> 23:36.300
For the two constant functions,
we see that the parity, or in other words, the eXclusive OR of the two outputs is 0,

214
23:36.300 --> 23:42.848
and for the two balance functions, the parity of the outputs is 1.

215
23:42.848 --> 23:49.710
So an equivalent way to
describe the parity problem in this particular case, where the function f takes
a single bit as input,

216
23:49.710 --> 23:54.300
or in other words, Deutsch's problem, is like you see here.

217
23:54.300 --> 24:00.660
The input is a function f
from one bit to one bit, and the output is 0 if f is constant

218
24:00.660 --> 24:06.240
and 1 if f is balanced.

219
24:06.240 --> 24:14.130
As I've already suggested, every classical query algorithm
that solves this problem must make at least two queries to f.

220
24:14.130 --> 24:22.080
If you learn just one of
the two output values of f, you still have no information at all about the parity of the two outputs.

221
24:22.080 --> 24:27.900
And this, by the way, is true
even for classical algorithms that make use of randomness.

222
24:27.900 --> 24:34.950
Randomness can sometimes be very useful for solving query problems, and we'll see an example
a bit later in the lesson,

223
24:34.950 --> 24:39.420
but randomness doesn't help here.

224
24:39.420 --> 24:46.590
So our algorithm from before is optimal among classical query algorithms
for Deutsch's problem.

225
24:46.590 --> 24:54.930
Now we'll take a look
at Deutsche's algorithm, which is a quantum query algorithm that solves Deutsch's
problem using a single query.

226
24:54.930 --> 24:59.580
And here is the algorithm
described as a quantum circuit.

227
24:59.580 --> 25:08.190
We have two qubits
initialized like you see here, with the top one initialized to cat 0 and the bottom one initialized to cat 1,

228
25:08.190 --> 25:13.020
and we'll see why we initialize these qubits like this shortly.

229
25:13.020 --> 25:20.190
We perform Hadamard
gates on the two qubits, feed them into the query gate, perform another Hadamard
gate on the top qubit,

230
25:20.190 --> 25:31.860
and then measure it. And the claim is that
the measurement outcome gives us, with certainty, the
correct answer to the problem.

231
25:31.860 --> 25:38.160
So let's analyze the
circuit one step at a time to see exactly how it works.

232
25:38.160 --> 25:45.930
The state of the two qubits after the first layer of Hadamard gates is the tensor product of
the minus and plus states.

233
25:45.930 --> 25:54.300
The Hadamard on top maps
the 0 state to a plus state, and the Hadamard on the bottom maps the 1 state to a minus state.

234
25:54.300 --> 25:59.940
The top qubit is on the right, and the bottom qubit is on the left, so this is the state that we get.

235
25:59.940 --> 26:06.663
It's very important that the bottom qubit is in a minus state, by the way, this wouldn't work if we
initialize the bottom qubit

236
26:06.663 --> 26:09.900
to a 0 state instead of a 1 state.

237
26:09.900 --> 26:14.190
We're going to expand this state
halfway, like you see here.

238
26:14.190 --> 26:22.260
The reason for doing that
isn't clear at this point, but it will be convenient
in just a moment.

239
26:22.260 --> 26:28.080
Next, let's think about
the state of the two qubits after the query gate is performed.

240
26:28.080 --> 26:36.120
The way the query gate
works is that it computes F on the standard basis
state of the top qubit and XOR is the value
onto the bottom qubit,

241
26:36.120 --> 26:40.350
and here we can see the
result of doing that.

242
26:40.350 --> 26:47.820
For the first term, the standard basis state
of the top qubit is 0, so f of zero gets XORed
onto the bottom qubit,

243
26:47.820 --> 26:53.970
and that works by linearity. And it's similar for the second term, except that the standard basis state

244
26:53.970 --> 26:59.520
for the top qubit is 1, so we XOR f of 1 onto the bottom qubit.

245
26:59.520 --> 27:08.250
And at this point, we can
simplify this expression by observing the formula
that you can see down here, which works when a is either 0 or 1.

246
27:08.250 --> 27:12.270
And we can simply check this for those two values separately.

247
27:12.270 --> 27:19.251
If a is equal to 0, then
XORing with a does nothing, and negative 1 to the power 0 is 1,

248
27:19.251 --> 27:25.680
so the two sides are equal. And if a is equal to 1, we get cat 1 minus cat
0 when we take the XOR,

249
27:25.680 --> 27:31.110
which is negative 1
times cat 0 minus cat 1.

250
27:31.110 --> 27:38.850
And if we use that formula
to simplify our state, where we take a is equal
to f of 0 on the left and a is equal to f of 1 on the right,

251
27:38.850 --> 27:42.690
we get the expression
that you see right here.

252
27:42.690 --> 27:49.290
So when we compare the two
quantum state vectors π1 and π2, we see that what the Uf gate does

253
27:49.290 --> 27:56.460
is effectively to put
one of the two values, f of 0 or f of 1, into the
exponent of negative 1,

254
27:56.460 --> 28:00.750
or in other words, into
the phase of each term.

255
28:00.750 --> 28:10.050
This is the reason for
initializing the bottom qubit to 1 and performing a Hadamard gate on it to create the minus state,
which allows this to happen.

256
28:10.050 --> 28:16.980
It's called the phase kickback phenomenon, and we'll come back to it in a few moments to have another look at it.

257
28:16.980 --> 28:27.120
It's pretty important, and we'll see it happening a
few more times in the lesson, as well as in later lessons.

258
28:27.120 --> 28:34.140
We can now simplify by pulling
the minus state back outside to get the expression
that you see right here.

259
28:34.140 --> 28:39.330
As an aside, it's kind
of interesting to notice that there isn't actually
any entanglement here.

260
28:39.330 --> 28:45.360
Both of these states are product states. So, well, entanglement
is extremely interesting,

261
28:45.360 --> 28:51.120
doesn't happen to be
playing any role at all in this particular algorithm.

262
28:51.120 --> 28:56.940
Let's clean this up a bit so that we have a little bit more room.

263
28:56.940 --> 29:03.210
What we can now do is to
pull a factor of negative 1 raised to the power f of zero outside

264
29:03.210 --> 29:07.800
to get the expression of the
state that you see right here.

265
29:07.800 --> 29:14.790
You'll notice that right here, we have eXclusive OR of f 0 and f 1 in the exponent of negative 1.

266
29:14.790 --> 29:22.200
We might expect that to
be f of 1 minus f of 0 because we pull the factor of negative 1 to the power f of 0 out,

267
29:22.200 --> 29:30.000
but we get the same
value if we take the XOR because these are bits, and the only thing that matters when we have an integer in
the exponent of negative 1

268
29:30.000 --> 29:36.300
is whether that integer is even or odd.

269
29:36.300 --> 29:43.410
Another way to express this
state is like we have here, where we're just considering
the two possible cases for the XOR.

270
29:43.410 --> 29:52.950
and that's a convenient
way to express the state as we consider the action
of the final Hadamard gate together with the measurement.

271
29:52.950 --> 29:59.550
When we perform the last
Hadamard gate on the top qubit, the plus state is
transformed into a 0 state

272
29:59.550 --> 30:10.980
and the minus state is
transformed into a 1 state, which we can write more
succinctly like this.

273
30:10.980 --> 30:19.230
And finally, when the
measurement is performed, the result we obtain is
therefore the XOR of f 0 and f 1,

274
30:19.230 --> 30:26.520
which is the value we're looking for, and that's how Deutsch's algorithm works.

275
30:26.520 --> 30:33.480
It's pretty simple, and if we ask ourselves what
it is that makes it work, allowing us to compute
the parity of two bits

276
30:33.480 --> 30:40.440
with a single query rather than two, a reasonable answer is
that it's interference.

277
30:40.440 --> 30:46.590
We're effectively
computing f of 0 and f of 1 at the same time, because we first performed
the Hadamard gate

278
30:46.590 --> 30:53.370
on the top qubit to put the input into f into
a super position of 0 and 1.

279
30:53.370 --> 30:59.580
And by means of the phase kickback together with the final Hadamard gate, we're essentially creating
constructive interference

280
30:59.580 --> 31:03.540
for the correct answer and destructive interference
for the wrong answer.

281
31:03.540 --> 31:08.160
So we don't see the wrong answer, we only see the correct answer.

282
31:08.160 --> 31:16.050
Let me now say a bit more about the phase kickback phenomenon just to see it from a
slightly different angle.

283
31:16.050 --> 31:23.790
First, let's observe
this very simple formula where b and c are arbitrary binary values.

284
31:23.790 --> 31:31.530
In short, XORing a bit b by the value 1 is the same thing as performing a NOT gate or an x operation on b,

285
31:31.530 --> 31:39.510
and of course, exploring
a bit b by the value 0 doesn't do anything to it, which is the same thing as performing the
identity operation on it.

286
31:39.510 --> 31:44.910
And we can express the identity operation as x to the power 0.

287
31:44.910 --> 31:51.900
So if we perform a Uf gate on two qubits in the standard basis
state cat b tensor cat a,

288
31:51.900 --> 31:57.600
we obtain this outcome, just by the definition of the Uf gate.

289
31:57.600 --> 32:05.400
and by using the formula, we can alternatively write that state like you see right here.

290
32:05.400 --> 32:12.240
This formula works for all choices of b, so by linearity, it works
for an arbitrary state SI

291
32:12.240 --> 32:15.870
in place of cat b.

292
32:15.870 --> 32:21.690
And in particular, if we want to, we can choose SI to be the minus state.

293
32:21.690 --> 32:26.700
And now here's the key to why the phase x kickback
phenomenon happens.

294
32:26.700 --> 32:33.360
It's because the x operation
applied to the minus state gives us negative 1 times the minus state.

295
32:33.360 --> 32:42.690
In mathematical terms, we say that the minus
state is an eigenvector of the x operation, with eigen value equal to negative 1.

296
32:42.690 --> 32:49.650
Eigenvectors and eigen values
are critically important in linear algebra as well
as in quantum information, and we'll have a lot
more to say about them

297
32:49.650 --> 32:52.680
as the series continues.

298
32:52.680 --> 32:57.570
But for now, all we need
is this simple formula.

299
32:57.570 --> 33:03.000
And using it, we can
simplify our state vector.

300
33:03.000 --> 33:10.380
And that right there is essentially the phase
kickback phenomenon written as a formula.

301
33:10.380 --> 33:17.880
It works because the minus
state is an eigenvector of the NOT operation having
eigen value negative one.

302
33:17.880 --> 33:27.780
We will generalize this in a
pretty major way in Lesson 7, when we turn to the phase
estimation procedure, which is what drives
Shor's factoring algorithm.

303
33:27.780 --> 33:34.230
We can see this formula in action in the analysis of Deutsch's
algorithm as follows.

304
33:34.230 --> 33:40.650
Prior to the query gate, our state is the tensor product of the minus and plus states.

305
33:40.650 --> 33:48.330
We then apply the query gate, and expanding out the plus
state gives us this state.

306
33:48.330 --> 33:56.010
We now apply the phase kickback formula to get this expression, and then the analysis
carries on as before.

307
33:56.010 --> 34:02.267
It's the same as before, but here we're just placing
a focus on the phase kickback so that we can recognize it

308
34:02.267 --> 34:06.360
and we can also be ready for
it when it comes up again.

309
34:06.360 --> 34:15.900
Next we'll turn to the
Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm, which is an extension
of Deutsch's algorithm that actually solves a couple
of different query problems.

310
34:15.900 --> 34:23.790
The advantage that
Deutsch's algorithm provides over classical algorithms
is pretty modest, one query versus two.

311
34:23.790 --> 34:31.350
The Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm increases that advantage somewhat, and I'll explain what I mean
by that when we get there.

312
34:31.350 --> 34:37.530
The Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm can be viewed as a natural and direct way of extending Deutsch's algorithm

313
34:37.530 --> 34:47.100
from functions from one bit to one bit to functions from n bits to one bit, or another words, functions of this form.

314
34:47.100 --> 34:55.080
As a quantum circuit, the Deutsch-Jozsa
algorithm looks like this, and I'm going to refer to this
as the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit

315
34:55.080 --> 35:05.160
just to draw a minor
distinction between this circuit and the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm itself because there's also a
classical post-processing step.

316
35:05.160 --> 35:11.190
The idea is that if we run
this circuit and then measure, we'll obtain some n bits string y

317
35:11.190 --> 35:15.150
that tells us something
about the function f.

318
35:15.150 --> 35:23.610
At this point, by the way, I haven't actually said
what the query problem is that we might hope to
solve with this circuit, that's coming up very soon.

319
35:23.610 --> 35:30.840
But the point is that
by running this circuit, we'll gain some information about f that can potentially help
us to solve query problems

320
35:30.840 --> 35:36.930
where f is the input. And like I said a moment ago, we can actually use this circuit

321
35:36.930 --> 35:40.290
to solve a couple of
different query problems.

322
35:40.290 --> 35:47.130
First, let's take a look
at the query problem known as the Deutsch-Jozsa problem, which is the problem that
the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit

323
35:47.130 --> 35:51.570
was originally intended to solve.

324
35:51.570 --> 36:00.930
The Deutsch-Jozsa problem is a generalization of Deutsch's problem, where the goal is to determine whether a given function
is constant or balanced.

325
36:00.930 --> 36:06.660
Notice that this isn't the natural way to generalize the parity problem
to functions of this form.

326
36:06.660 --> 36:12.690
Here we're not computing the parity, the task is to output 0 if
the function f is constant

327
36:12.690 --> 36:17.700
and 1 if the function f is balanced.

328
36:17.700 --> 36:24.450
The first thing to notice about
this problem is that when n, the number of input bits to
the function f, is at least 2,

329
36:24.450 --> 36:29.280
there are choices for the function that are neither constant nor balanced.

330
36:29.280 --> 36:35.850
For example, here's a
function from 2 bits to 1 bit that's neither constant nor balanced.

331
36:35.850 --> 36:42.840
It's not constant because both binary values
appear among the outputs, and it's not balanced
because the two output values

332
36:42.840 --> 36:48.990
appear with different frequencies. 0 appears three times
and 1 appears just once.

333
36:48.990 --> 36:56.790
In order to be balanced,
the outputs 0 and 1 have to occur exactly
the same number of times.

334
36:56.790 --> 37:04.200
The fact that there are functions that are neither constant nor balanced when n is at least 2 is okay though, we're just gonna consider
functions like that

335
37:04.200 --> 37:11.160
as "don't care" inputs. So in other words, this
is a promise problem.

336
37:11.160 --> 37:14.460
And here's a precise
statement of the problem.

337
37:14.460 --> 37:22.200
We're promised that the input function f is either constant or balanced, and the goal is to figure
out which one it is.

338
37:22.200 --> 37:29.070
And we're not responsible for what happens if the input
doesn't meet the promise.

339
37:29.070 --> 37:35.730
The Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm,
which solves this problem, is first to run the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit and then output 0

340
37:35.730 --> 37:42.660
if the string that we
obtain from the measurements is the all-zero string
and output 1 otherwise.

341
37:42.660 --> 37:48.180
Another way to say that is that we output the OR of
the bits that we measure.

342
37:48.180 --> 37:54.900
To analyze the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm, it'll be helpful to
first take a few moments to think about Hadamard gates.

343
37:54.900 --> 38:01.260
We can, of course, describe the Hadamard
operation as a matrix, but we can also describe
it in terms of its action

344
38:01.260 --> 38:06.720
on standard basis states,
as you see right here.

345
38:06.720 --> 38:17.580
These two equations can be
combined into a single equation, which describes how a
Hadamard operation works for a being either of
the two binary values,

346
38:17.580 --> 38:29.580
and we can go a little bit further and express what we
obtain as a sum like this.

347
38:29.580 --> 38:41.760
Using that formula, we can come up with a formula that describes how a layer
of Hadamard gates works, where we apply one Hadamard
gate to each of n qubits.

348
38:41.760 --> 38:45.210
Here we're describing this
action on standard basis states.

349
38:45.210 --> 38:52.830
And to be clear about the notation, when we write h tensor n like this, where the tensor n part is a superscript,

350
38:52.830 --> 39:01.830
what we mean is the n fold
tensor product of H with itself, or in other words, n copies
of h all tensor together.

351
39:01.830 --> 39:07.830
We're applying this operation
to a standard basis state, and here I'm following the
convention that Qiskit uses

352
39:07.830 --> 39:13.140
to index binary strings, just because it's a good time
to introduce that convention.

353
39:13.140 --> 39:22.740
So x0 is a bit, x1 is a bit,
and so on with n bits in total, and the bits are ordered as
you see here on the screen.

354
39:22.740 --> 39:29.370
You can think about this
way of indexing bits as corresponding to their significance if we view strings as
representing integers

355
39:29.370 --> 39:33.870
in binary notation, for instance.

356
39:33.870 --> 39:40.740
If we apply a Hadamard gate
to each of these qubits, we can alternatively express the result as the n fold tensor product

357
39:40.740 --> 39:49.320
of a Hadamar gate applied to each qubit, and then we can apply our formula to each one of the tensor factors.

358
39:49.320 --> 39:55.620
And here we're using the
names y and minus 1 down to y1 in place of b in the formula,

359
39:55.620 --> 40:04.050
so these are binary values. And we're making sure to use a new name each time we use the formula.

360
40:04.050 --> 40:11.460
If we then expand everything out using the multilinearity
of tensor products, we get the expression
that you see right here.

361
40:11.460 --> 40:18.180
And to be clear, the n sums are being
combined into a single sum, but we're still summing
over all the possible values

362
40:18.180 --> 40:22.080
for the individual binary values.

363
40:22.080 --> 40:26.340
Now let's clean things up so that we can go a little bit further.

364
40:26.340 --> 40:33.150
And the next step is to
introduce a new operation on strings called the binary dot product.

365
40:33.150 --> 40:37.800
This is an operation on binary strings having the same length.

366
40:37.800 --> 40:45.390
And what the binary dot product of two strings x and y
of the same length is, is the eXclusive OR or the parity

367
40:45.390 --> 40:48.840
of the products of the individual bits.

368
40:48.840 --> 40:55.320
You could also say that it's the XOR of the logical and of the individual bits, because the and is the
same thing as the product

369
40:55.320 --> 41:01.350
for binary values. Yet another way to describe
it is that it's 1 or 0

370
41:01.350 --> 41:07.470
depending on whether
the sum of the products of the individual bits is odd or even.

371
41:07.470 --> 41:15.090
It's very much like an inner product if we think about strings
as vectors of binary values, but where we compute Modulo-2,

372
41:15.090 --> 41:19.290
or in other words, we take the remainder after dividing by 2.

373
41:19.290 --> 41:24.360
It's not really an inner product though, so it deserves a different name.

374
41:24.360 --> 41:30.630
In the case at hand, we can use the binary dot
product to make our formula for the action of a layer of Hadamard gate

375
41:30.630 --> 41:36.000
on standard basis states more succinct, and here it is right here.

376
41:36.000 --> 41:42.300
We're using the fact that
because this sum right here is appearing in the
exponent of negative 1,

377
41:42.300 --> 41:51.210
all that matters is whether
or not it's even or odd, but otherwise, it's basically just a condensed
version of our formula.

378
41:51.210 --> 41:57.810
By the way, the binary
dot product is symmetric in the sense that x dot
y and y dot x are equal,

379
41:57.810 --> 42:02.730
so we are free to swap the
ordering whenever that's useful.

380
42:02.730 --> 42:09.090
And now that we have that formula, it'll be pretty easy to analyze
the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit.

381
42:09.090 --> 42:16.890
We start out with n qubits in the 0 state and the bottom qubit in the 1 state, and we perform Hadamard
gates on all of them.

382
42:16.890 --> 42:21.330
So this is the state of the
n + 1 qubits that we get.

383
42:21.330 --> 42:25.380
We are treating the
bottom qubit separately because that's gonna be convenient.

384
42:25.380 --> 42:30.570
And again, we're gonna see the phase
kickback phenomenon happening.

385
42:30.570 --> 42:38.400
We can get this expression
by using our formula, where we substitute the
all-zero string for x and substitute x for y,

386
42:38.400 --> 42:43.890
noting that the binary dot
product of the all-zero string with any string is 0.

387
42:43.890 --> 42:50.940
But we can also just reason this directly. We're taking the tensor
product of n plus states, and this is what we get,

388
42:50.940 --> 42:59.280
tensor to the minus state. Then the UF gate is applied, and here's where the phase
kickback phenomenon happens.

389
42:59.280 --> 43:04.140
The value f of x is getting
XORed onto the minus state for each x in the sum.

390
43:04.140 --> 43:09.330
So f of x gets kicked into the phase.

391
43:09.330 --> 43:16.980
We now apply another
layer of Hadamard gates just to the top n qubits, and this time, we really
do need the formula.

392
43:16.980 --> 43:22.890
And when we apply it and do just a little
bit of simplification, we get this state right here.

393
43:22.890 --> 43:27.540
So that's our final state just
prior to the measurements.

394
43:27.540 --> 43:34.950
The state looks a little bit complicated, and it's difficult to simplify it because we don't really know
anything about the function f.

395
43:34.950 --> 43:41.340
But remember, that all
we really need to know is whether or not the measurements
all yield the outcome 0,

396
43:41.340 --> 43:45.990
because that's what determines what our answer is to the problem.

397
43:45.990 --> 43:51.540
If we see that every
measurement outcome is 0, we conclude that the function is constant.

398
43:51.540 --> 43:59.330
And if any one of the
measurement outcomes is 1, we conclude that the function is balanced.

399
43:59.330 --> 44:04.200
So let's calculate the probability to get the all-zero string
from the measurements.

400
44:04.200 --> 44:11.100
And that turns out to be the one result that's actually easy to calculate, because the binary dot
product of the all-zero string

401
44:11.100 --> 44:18.570
with any string is zero. If we examine our vector and
we think about what happens when y is the all-zero string,

402
44:18.570 --> 44:26.460
we get this expression right
here for the probability to get the all-zero string
from the measurements.

403
44:26.460 --> 44:34.590
And considering the two possible cases where f is constant and f is balanced, we see that the probability to
get the all-zero string is 1

404
44:34.590 --> 44:39.600
in the case that f is constant, and zero when f is balanced.

405
44:39.600 --> 44:46.080
When f is constant, the sum is either 2 to the
n or negative 2 to the n, and dividing by two to the n

406
44:46.080 --> 44:49.230
and taking the absolute
value squared yields 1.

407
44:49.230 --> 44:52.920
And when f is balanced, the sum equals 0.

408
44:52.920 --> 45:02.029
That's because we'll get
positive 1 and negative 1 an equal number of times,
so they all cancel out.

409
45:02.029 --> 45:09.060
So that's it. The Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm
solves the Deutsch-Jozsa problem using a single query,

410
45:09.060 --> 45:17.130
and there's no error. Assuming the operations
are all done perfectly, it's correct every single time.

411
45:17.130 --> 45:21.660
So how does that compare with
what we can do classically?

412
45:21.660 --> 45:28.470
Well, if we insist on a
deterministic algorithm that gets the answer
correct every single time, then in the worst case,

413
45:28.470 --> 45:34.500
we need 2 to the n minus 1 plus 1 queries, and that's because we
have to query the function

414
45:34.500 --> 45:40.080
on more than half of its inputs to be sure about the solution.

415
45:40.080 --> 45:46.800
Even if we query the function on 2 to the n minus 1
different input strings, it's possible that we'll
see the same output value

416
45:46.800 --> 45:52.980
every single time, and that could be because
the function is constant, or it could be that it's actually balanced

417
45:52.980 --> 45:59.370
and we've just been incredibly unlucky having seen the same output
value every single time.

418
45:59.370 --> 46:07.830
So that's a huge advantage
of quantum over classical, a single query versus
exponentially many queries.

419
46:07.830 --> 46:15.510
However, if we use a
probabilistic query algorithm and we accept a small probability that it answers incorrectly,

420
46:15.510 --> 46:19.170
then we actually only need a few queries.

421
46:19.170 --> 46:25.530
In particular, if we
randomly choose k strings and evaluate the function
on those random strings,

422
46:25.530 --> 46:30.090
then we are pretty likely to be able to figure out the right answer.

423
46:30.090 --> 46:36.930
Specifically, we answer 0 or constant when we get the same function
value every single time and 1 or balanced

424
46:36.930 --> 46:40.560
whenever we see two
different function values.

425
46:40.560 --> 46:47.850
If we do that, we'll always be correct when
the function is constant because, of course, we'll always see the same
output value in this case.

426
46:47.850 --> 46:53.310
And if f is balanced, we're very likely to see
two different output values.

427
46:53.310 --> 47:00.210
The chance that we don't see
both output values in this case is the same as the chance that we have of flipping a coin k times

428
47:00.210 --> 47:03.930
and getting the same
result every single time.

429
47:03.930 --> 47:12.270
So for example, if we
set k to be equal to 11, the probability of getting a wrong answer is less than a 10th of a percent.

430
47:12.270 --> 47:20.550
So especially when we consider the fact that quantum computers are never going to be perfect in reality, we don't actually get that
big of an advantage here,

431
47:20.550 --> 47:30.240
but we're making progress, and we do have a quantifiable advantage of quantum over classical that goes beyond Deutsch's algorithm.

432
47:30.240 --> 47:38.790
We can also use the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit to solve a different query problem known as the Bernstein-Vazirani problem.

433
47:38.790 --> 47:46.830
Here's a statement of that problem. The input is a function
from n bits to 1 bit, just like the Deutsch-Jozsa problem,

434
47:46.830 --> 47:50.220
and again, it's a promise problem.

435
47:50.220 --> 47:58.380
This time, the promise is that there exists some n bits string s for which the function f
works as you see right here,

436
47:58.380 --> 48:05.011
where the output is given
by the binary dot product of the input with this string s,

437
48:05.011 --> 48:12.270
and the goal is simply
to find the string s. So we can imagine that the
string s is hidden in some sense,

438
48:12.270 --> 48:19.380
but we can learn about it
by making queries to f, and our goal is to find
this hidden string.

439
48:19.380 --> 48:28.830
To be clear, most functions
won't satisfy this promise, but as usual, we only care about the
input functions that do.

440
48:28.830 --> 48:35.310
As it turns out, the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit actually solves this problem
right out of the box.

441
48:35.310 --> 48:42.900
If we run it for a
function like we have here that satisfies the
promise for some string s, the measurements will reveal the string s

442
48:42.900 --> 48:47.430
with no post-processing required.

443
48:47.430 --> 48:50.910
So let's see how this works.

444
48:50.910 --> 48:56.400
We've already analyzed
the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit, so we can actually just
skip right to the end.

445
48:56.400 --> 49:06.570
Here's the expression that we
had from before for the state just prior to the measurements, and that expression was
valid for any function f.

446
49:06.570 --> 49:14.230
And now, if we substitute
in what we're promised about the function f and simplify,

447
49:14.230 --> 49:20.130
we get the minus state
for the bottom qubit tensored with cat s for the top n qubits.

448
49:20.130 --> 49:24.630
And so we get s when we measure.

449
49:24.630 --> 49:30.630
There is some work to do to perform the simplifications
that I've shown here, and I won't go through that in this video,

450
49:30.630 --> 49:37.890
but there is more detail about it in the textbook content for this series, which you can find by following the link in the description of the video,

451
49:37.890 --> 49:43.140
or just try it for
yourself for some practice.

452
49:43.140 --> 49:52.050
So what we found is that
the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit solves the Bernstein-Vazirani
problem with a single query.

453
49:52.050 --> 49:58.710
It's not too hard to show
that any classical algorithm, whether it's deterministic
or probabilistic, needs at least n queries

454
49:58.710 --> 50:04.770
to solve the Bernstein-Vazirani problem for the simple reason that we need n bits of
information to recover s,

455
50:04.770 --> 50:09.330
and each query gives us at
most 1 bit of information.

456
50:09.330 --> 50:16.050
So we get another advantage of quantum over classical
query algorithms, one query for quantum algorithms,

457
50:16.050 --> 50:20.610
n queries for classical algorithms.

458
50:20.610 --> 50:28.560
It's worth taking just a moment to speak about the
nomenclature that's used in the context of this problem and a little bit about the history.

459
50:28.560 --> 50:37.230
People sometimes refer to the algorithm that I just described as being the Bernstein-Vazirani algorithm, but it's really just the
Deutsch-Jozsa circuit,

460
50:37.230 --> 50:42.898
and that's something that was,
in fact, very clearly stated in Bernstein and Vazirani's work.

461
50:42.898 --> 50:49.680
So it is a little bit strange that it's called the
Bernstein-Vazirani algorithm because it's pretty much the same thing as the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm

462
50:49.680 --> 50:55.080
minus the post-processing. Bernstein and Vazirani did,
however, go a step further.

463
50:55.080 --> 51:01.710
They defined a recursive
version of this problem, where you basically
have to solve instances of the Bernstein-Vazirani problem

464
51:01.710 --> 51:07.560
to unlock new instances of the problem that are arranged in a
complicated tree-like pattern.

465
51:07.560 --> 51:14.880
It's a highly contrived problem, but the point is that by
defining a problem in this way, they could effectively stretch out

466
51:14.880 --> 51:19.710
the one versus n query separation between quantum and classical.

467
51:19.710 --> 51:29.220
And what they obtained is
the very first known example of a so-called super polynomial advantage of quantum over probabilistic algorithms.

468
51:29.220 --> 51:37.950
This recursive version of the
Bernstein-Vazirani problem also turned out much later
to be very interesting in computational complexity
theory for different reasons.

469
51:37.950 --> 51:44.640
Anyway, the point is that
Bernstein and Vazirani certainly deserve recognition for their important contributions,

470
51:44.640 --> 51:53.040
but it really doesn't make
sense to refer to this as the Bernstein-Vazirani algorithm, it's basically just the
Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm.

471
51:53.040 --> 51:59.550
In the last part of the lesson, we'll take a look at one
more quantum query algorithm known as Simon's algorithm.

472
51:59.550 --> 52:07.170
You'll see a clear similarity
between this algorithm and the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm, but it is different, and more importantly,

473
52:07.170 --> 52:13.380
it reveals a much stronger advantage of quantum over classical
query algorithms.

474
52:13.380 --> 52:22.680
Specifically, it gives us a
provable exponential advantage of quantum over classical algorithms, even probabilistic ones.

475
52:22.680 --> 52:30.870
The problem it solves is a bit artificial, and it's hard to imagine a situation in which solving this
problem would be useful,

476
52:30.870 --> 52:37.350
but it did directly inspire
Peter Shor's discovery of a quantum algorithm
for integer factorization,

477
52:37.350 --> 52:46.410
and that very strongly supports
this idea of the query model as a Petri dish in which quantum algorithmic
ideas can be developed.

478
52:46.410 --> 52:56.010
Let's start with the query problem that Simon's algorithm solves, which, as you might have guessed,
is called Simon's problem.

479
52:56.010 --> 53:03.180
Here's a statement of the problem, and we're going to need to unpack it to understand what it's all about.

480
53:03.180 --> 53:09.360
The first thing to
notice is that this time, the input function f maps n
bits strings to m bits strings

481
53:09.360 --> 53:14.460
where m is some positive integer that isn't equal to one in general.

482
53:14.460 --> 53:22.770
It's a promise problem. And like the Bernstein-Vazirani problem, the promise involves some string s that we can view as being a hidden string,

483
53:22.770 --> 53:29.610
and also like the
Bernstein-Vazirani problem, the goal is to output
this hidden string s.

484
53:29.610 --> 53:36.180
The promise is more
complicated this time though, so let's take it apart and
understand what it's saying.

485
53:36.180 --> 53:42.810
To begin, let's just read it. It says that there exists a string s having length equal to n

486
53:42.810 --> 53:50.460
such that a particular "if"
and "only if" condition is true for all choices of n bits strings x and y.

487
53:50.460 --> 53:59.010
Specifically, it must
be the case that f of x is equal to f of y if and only if one of
two possibilities holds.

488
53:59.010 --> 54:06.630
The first possibility is that x equals y, and the second possibility is that by taking the
bitwise eXclusive OR of x

489
54:06.630 --> 54:10.710
in the hidden string s, we get Y.

490
54:10.710 --> 54:15.600
This turns out to be a
pretty strict promise in the sense that most
functions won't satisfy it.

491
54:15.600 --> 54:20.850
Only very special functions
satisfy this condition.

492
54:20.850 --> 54:30.390
Now, to get a better grasp on this promise and therefore on the problem itself, we'll consider two main cases.

493
54:30.390 --> 54:34.560
The first case is that s
is the all-zero string.

494
54:34.560 --> 54:41.520
In this case, we can simplify the "if"
and "only if" statement in the promise because the bitwise
eXclusive OR of any string x

495
54:41.520 --> 54:45.570
with the all-zero string
is simply the string x.

496
54:45.570 --> 54:53.700
So the condition simplifies
to f of x is equal to f of y if and only if x equals y.

497
54:53.700 --> 54:58.140
And that's just another way of saying that f is a one to one function.

498
54:58.140 --> 55:04.440
In other words, the string f of x must be unique
for each possible string x.

499
55:04.440 --> 55:12.780
So if f is a one to one function, then the promise is indeed satisfied, specifically for s being
the all-zero string,

500
55:12.780 --> 55:17.670
and in this case, that's
the correct output.

501
55:17.670 --> 55:26.190
The second case is that s
is not the all-zero string, and what this implies is that the function f must be two to one.

502
55:26.190 --> 55:33.900
So for every input string x, there's exactly one other string that f maps to the same
string that x maps to,

503
55:33.900 --> 55:42.180
and moreover, the other string
must be the string we get by taking the bitwise
eXclusive OR of x with s.

504
55:42.180 --> 55:48.840
Another way of saying this
is that every n bit string x has a partner, and that partner is the string that we get

505
55:48.840 --> 55:53.160
by taking the bitwise eXclusive OR with s.

506
55:53.160 --> 56:01.530
Any two partners must give
us the same output string if we plug them into f, and no other strings are allowed to give us
that same output string.

507
56:01.530 --> 56:08.130
So these are necessarily distinct strings that partners produce.

508
56:08.130 --> 56:12.660
Here's an example of a function like this described by its table of values.

509
56:12.660 --> 56:16.920
So this is a function
from 3 bits to 5 bits.

510
56:16.920 --> 56:25.902
If we stare at this table
of values for a while, we find that the promise is
satisfied for the string 011.

511
56:25.902 --> 56:32.010
000 and 011 are partners. XORing either one of them
by s gives us the other,

512
56:32.010 --> 56:41.160
and they take the same output value, which is 10011 in this particular case, and no other strings produce
that same output string.

513
56:41.160 --> 56:48.960
001 and 010 are partners because XORing either
one by s gives the other, and they produce the same output value,

514
56:48.960 --> 56:52.440
which again, isn't produced
by any other string.

515
56:52.440 --> 57:01.398
And the situation is
similar for 100 and 111 as well as 101 and 110.

516
57:01.398 --> 57:08.130
So if the input to the
problem is this function, the correct answer is the string 011.

517
57:08.130 --> 57:15.120
Like I said before, most functions don't satisfy this promise, it's a very specific condition.

518
57:15.120 --> 57:20.640
It should also be noted that
if the promise is satisfied, it can only be satisfied for one string s.

519
57:20.640 --> 57:25.380
So there's always only one
correct answer to this problem.

520
57:25.380 --> 57:34.080
So that is Simon's problem. Like I said, it's hard to imagine a practical situation in which you'd wanna solve this problem,

521
57:34.080 --> 57:42.360
but that isn't the point. The point is to try to figure out what quantum computers are good at, and it turns out that they're far superior

522
57:42.360 --> 57:46.680
to classical algorithms for
solving this particular problem.

523
57:46.680 --> 57:52.650
Now let's take a look
at Simon's algorithm, which solves Simon's problem.

524
57:52.650 --> 58:00.600
The algorithm consists of
running the quantum circuit that you see here several times, followed by a classical
post-processing step,

525
58:00.600 --> 58:05.970
and we'll be more specific about what several
times means a bit later.

526
58:05.970 --> 58:13.800
The circuit looks very similar
to the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit, this time because the function
f maps n bits to m bits,

527
58:13.800 --> 58:19.980
the query gate is different. Rather than just a single
qubit on the bottom, we now have m qubits on the bottom

528
58:19.980 --> 58:23.850
and n on the top like before.

529
58:23.850 --> 58:30.900
A key difference is that we're
not setting up a minus state or multiple minus states on the bottom.

530
58:30.900 --> 58:37.980
These bottom qubits are all
initialized to the 0 state, and those states go straight
into the query gate.

531
58:37.980 --> 58:45.600
So there won't be any phase kickback involved in this algorithm, it's just not how this one works.

532
58:45.600 --> 58:50.910
Other than the differences
I just mentioned though, it looks very similar to
the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit.

533
58:50.910 --> 58:58.350
We apply a layer of Hadamard gates, then we apply a query gate one time, and then we apply another
layer of Hadamard gates

534
58:58.350 --> 59:03.750
followed by standard basis measurements of the top n qubits.

535
59:03.750 --> 59:12.300
The idea is that each time we
run this circuit and measure, we'll get some string y that tells us something
about the hidden string s

536
59:12.300 --> 59:20.670
in Simon's problem. And by running the circuit
several times independently, we will have gathered enough
statistical evidence about s

537
59:20.670 --> 59:24.660
to be able to figure out what
it is with high confidence.

538
59:24.660 --> 59:31.950
Now let's analyze the quantum
circuit for Simon's algorithm to see what it does.

539
59:31.950 --> 59:38.520
The state after the first
layer of Hadamard gates looks like this, similar to what we had for
the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm.

540
59:38.520 --> 59:48.330
Except this time, the bottom m qubits are all in the 0 state
rather than in minus states.

541
59:48.330 --> 59:56.310
After the query gate is performed, we see that the value f of x has been written onto the
bottom or leftmost m qubits,

542
59:56.310 --> 60:01.320
and that's because f of x has been XORed onto the all-zero string.

543
60:01.320 --> 60:05.820
So again, there's no phase kickback happening in this algorithm.

544
60:05.820 --> 60:08.880
We then perform the second
layer of Hadamard gates.

545
60:08.880 --> 60:16.770
And using the same formula as before for the action of a
layer of Hadamard gates on a standard basis
state, cat x in this case,

546
60:16.770 --> 60:22.860
as it was in the original formula, we obtain this state right here, where the action of the Hadamard gates

547
60:22.860 --> 60:32.130
has been made more apparent. But if we want to, we can also write the state
in a more compact form like we have right here.

548
60:32.130 --> 60:39.840
At this point, we measure the top n qubits to obtain some end bit string y, and we just need to figure
out what the probabilities are

549
60:39.840 --> 60:47.160
for the different strings. And that'll help us to understand
what information we get from this string y about the string s

550
60:47.160 --> 60:50.970
that's hidden inside of the function f.

551
60:50.970 --> 60:59.430
We're going to need
some more room for this, and we really don't need
the circuit diagram anymore, so let's get rid of it and give ourselves some
more space for the analysis.

552
60:59.430 --> 61:07.500
Here's the state just
prior to the measurements, which are standard basis measurements of the top or rightmost n qubits.

553
61:07.500 --> 61:12.270
So the measurement
corresponds to the second cat.

554
61:12.270 --> 61:19.440
Let's denote by p of y, the probability that the measurements give us the string y for each possible y.

555
61:19.440 --> 61:28.530
And if we follow the rules from Lesson 2, we get that each of these probabilities is the Euclidean norm squared of whatever vector is tensored
to the standard basis state,

556
61:28.530 --> 61:32.340
corresponding to why in
our quantum state vector.

557
61:32.340 --> 61:36.360
That gives us this expression right here.

558
61:36.360 --> 61:43.410
Now, to get a better handle
on these probabilities, we're gonna need to make
use of some notation, and you might already be
familiar with this notation

559
61:43.410 --> 61:47.400
because it's pretty common in mathematics.

560
61:47.400 --> 61:55.110
First, when we refer to the
range of the function f, we just mean the set of all the strings that can come out of this function.

561
61:55.110 --> 62:02.400
So it's the set of all f of x ranging over all the possible
choices of an input string x.

562
62:02.400 --> 62:08.670
Second, we're gonna use this notation that you see right here to mean the set of all the input strings x

563
62:08.670 --> 62:15.150
that f maps to a given string z, for whatever choice of
z we wanna consider.

564
62:15.150 --> 62:23.310
It kind of looks like the
inverse of the function f, but it's not really the inverse because f is not necessarily invertible.

565
62:23.310 --> 62:30.630
We also see that we have
a set as the argument on the left hand side, and in this case, it's the set containing
just a single string z,

566
62:30.630 --> 62:38.070
and that's the clue we need to recognize that we're not talking about
the inverse of the function f, this is called the pre-image.

567
62:38.070 --> 62:44.820
The pre-image can be
defined more generally for any set given as an argument, not just the set containing
a single element,

568
62:44.820 --> 62:51.720
but this is all that we're gonna need. It's not the greatest
notation in the world because it's easy to
confuse it with the inverse,

569
62:51.720 --> 62:55.980
but it's clear enough
and it's widely used, so we're gonna go with it.

570
62:55.980 --> 63:05.970
And now if we use this notation, we can rewrite the vector that we're taking the
Euclidean norm squared of to get the probability for
measuring each string y.

571
63:05.970 --> 63:14.580
We're doing this because we need to see
what the coefficients are for each individual standard basis state, and that's not clear from
this expression right here,

572
63:14.580 --> 63:21.090
because, in general, we may
have multiple choices of x giving us the same string f of x.

573
63:21.090 --> 63:28.410
In essence, all we're doing
is splitting up the sum over x by first summing overall
z in the range of f,

574
63:28.410 --> 63:34.830
and then inside of that sum, summing over all x in the pre-image of z, or to be more accurate,

575
63:34.830 --> 63:39.570
the pre-image of the set
containing the string z.

576
63:39.570 --> 63:43.890
That lets us replace f of x with z inside of the cat right here.

577
63:43.890 --> 63:52.050
And the sum overall, the different strings
x that f maps to each z are collected into the
coefficient for each cat.

578
63:52.050 --> 63:58.620
We're basically putting strings into bins, summing over the bins, and then summing over
the strings in each bin,

579
63:58.620 --> 64:01.680
but that's equivalent to just
summing over all the strings.

580
64:01.680 --> 64:09.240
So we do obtain an expression that's equivalent to the
one that we started with,

581
64:09.240 --> 64:12.900
and now we can compute the
Euclidean norm squared.

582
64:12.900 --> 64:19.200
It's just the sum of the squares of the absolute values
of the coefficients, and so, we get this expression right here

583
64:19.200 --> 64:23.400
for our probabilities.

584
64:23.400 --> 64:30.480
Of course, give yourself
time to verify this, if you choose to do that, it takes time to get used to all this

585
64:30.480 --> 64:37.500
and to be able to perform
these calculations, and the more practice you give yourself, the easier it'll become.

586
64:37.500 --> 64:42.900
So far, we haven't actually
made use of the promise in Simon's problem at all.

587
64:42.900 --> 64:52.380
Our analysis of these probabilities actually works for any function f, but now it's time to think about Simon's
problems specifically.

588
64:52.380 --> 64:56.790
We're going to break things down into the same two cases
that we had before.

589
64:56.790 --> 65:03.720
The first case is that s
is the all-zero string, and the second case is that
s is not the all-zero string.

590
65:03.720 --> 65:09.990
In the first case, that
s is the all-zero string, things are pretty simple.

591
65:09.990 --> 65:16.890
In this case, as we saw before, we have that f is a one to one function, so there's a single string x

592
65:16.890 --> 65:21.750
that gets mapped to each of the
strings z in the range of f.

593
65:21.750 --> 65:28.680
That makes the absolute value squared of the sum over those strings equal to 1 because there's just a
single term in the sum,

594
65:28.680 --> 65:39.450
it's either plus 1 or minus 1, but it doesn't matter which because we take the
absolute value squared, and so we get one.

595
65:39.450 --> 65:48.930
There are 2 to the n
elements in the range of f, and we know that because f is one to one, so there's one string in the
range for each input string.

596
65:48.930 --> 65:57.060
And if we evaluate the entire expression, we find that each string y appears with probability
one over two to the n.

597
65:57.060 --> 66:04.470
So in other words, the
measurements give us a string y chosen uniformly at random.

598
66:04.470 --> 66:10.770
That might not seem all that useful, but we will, in fact, be able
to distinguish this behavior from the behavior we get in the case

599
66:10.770 --> 66:16.530
that s is not the all-zero string, and we'll see how that goes shortly.

600
66:16.530 --> 66:25.200
For now though, we simply observe that if
f satisfies the promise in Simon's problem in the case that s is the all-zero string,

601
66:25.200 --> 66:29.340
then the result of the measurements is a uniform random string.

602
66:29.340 --> 66:37.860
Now let's move on to the second case, which is that the promise
is satisfied for a string s that's not the all zero-string.

603
66:37.860 --> 66:45.540
In this case, as we discussed before, each string z in the range of f has exactly two strings that map to it,

604
66:45.540 --> 66:52.950
because every string has a partner, and each pair of partners
maps to some unique string, and specifically, each string's partner

605
66:52.950 --> 66:57.515
is the string we get by XORing with s.

606
66:57.515 --> 67:04.860
So if we pick any string
z in the range of f, and we give the name w to either one of the
strings that f maps to z,

607
67:04.860 --> 67:11.640
then the XOR of w with s is the
other string that maps to z.

608
67:11.640 --> 67:17.850
Looking at just the one term in our sum that corresponds to whatever string z in the range that we have in mind,

609
67:17.850 --> 67:22.440
we see that we can
write it more explicitly as we have right here.

610
67:22.440 --> 67:27.720
We have two strings in the pre-image of z, w and w XORed with s.

611
67:27.720 --> 67:38.340
So we can write the sum
as you see on the screen, and now what we can do is we can pull out a factor of
negative 1 to the power w.y.

612
67:38.340 --> 67:44.430
That factor is going to be
either plus 1 or minus 1, so it goes away when we
take the absolute value,

613
67:44.430 --> 67:48.810
and what we're left with is
this expression right here.

614
67:48.810 --> 67:56.250
The details aren't all shown here, and it's not necessarily
obvious that it works this way, but you can check that these
two expressions are equal

615
67:56.250 --> 68:04.170
by going back to the definition
of the binary dot product and thinking about what happens when these things are in
the exponent of negative 1,

616
68:04.170 --> 68:09.510
not unlike what we had for the
Bernstein-Vazirani problem.

617
68:09.510 --> 68:13.980
Finally, we can break this
expression up into two cases.

618
68:13.980 --> 68:23.400
It's 4 when the binary dot
product of s and y is 0, and it's 0 when the binary
dot product of s and y is 1.

619
68:23.400 --> 68:31.380
Notice in particular that
there's no dependence at all here on w or z, it only depends on s and y.

620
68:31.380 --> 68:37.320
The reason this happens is
because of the very specific and special nature of the promise.

621
68:37.320 --> 68:43.290
In essence, this is why the promise was formulated in this way, so it would all work out like this.

622
68:43.290 --> 68:49.620
Again, every string has a partner, which we get by XORing with
this one hidden string s,

623
68:49.620 --> 68:53.760
and that's what makes this all happen.

624
68:53.760 --> 68:58.710
We can now go back to the
expression for the probabilities and plug things in.

625
68:58.710 --> 69:04.860
When s is not the all-zero string, there are 2 to the n minus 1
elements in the range of f,

626
69:04.860 --> 69:12.900
which is half of the
number of input strings, and plugging in the
values we just calculated gives this formula right here.

627
69:12.900 --> 69:21.630
So this time, y is not a
completely random string, but rather y is uniform over exactly half of the n bit strings,

628
69:21.630 --> 69:29.130
and specifically, it's
uniform over those strings that have binary dot
product equal to 0 with s.

629
69:29.130 --> 69:36.540
Now that we know how the circuit
for Simon's algorithm works and specifically what
the probabilities are for the different measurement outcomes,

630
69:36.540 --> 69:41.820
it remains to explain how this helps us to solve Simon's problem.

631
69:41.820 --> 69:49.290
Summarizing what we just learned, if it's the case that the function f satisfies the promise in Simon's problem,

632
69:49.290 --> 69:55.560
when the hidden string s
is the all-zero string, we obtain a completely random
string from the measurements,

633
69:55.560 --> 69:59.190
where each end bit string
y is equally likely.

634
69:59.190 --> 70:06.600
If on the other hand, the function f satisfies the promise for a different string s, one that's not equal
to the all-zero string,

635
70:06.600 --> 70:16.620
then we get a random string y having binary dot product
equal to 0 with s, and among all of those strings,
each y is equally likely.

636
70:16.620 --> 70:23.220
But we'll never get a string y having binary dot product
equal to 1 with s.

637
70:23.220 --> 70:31.560
The question becomes, "Is this enough information
to determine s?" And the answer, as I've
already suggested, is yes,

638
70:31.560 --> 70:36.450
provided that we run the
circuit enough times.

639
70:36.450 --> 70:43.020
Specifically, let's suppose
that we run the circuit k times, where K is equal to n plus r,

640
70:43.020 --> 70:48.330
where r is some number that's going to control the
likelihood that we recover s.

641
70:48.330 --> 70:56.160
Just as an example, if
we choose r to be 10, we'll be successful with
probability greater than 99.9%,

642
70:56.160 --> 71:00.000
so we don't need r to be all that large.

643
71:00.000 --> 71:09.060
In general, the probability of failure is less than the probability
of flipping a fair coin r times and getting heads every single time.

644
71:09.060 --> 71:16.950
So if 99.9% isn't good
enough, then take r to be 20, and the chance of failure is
less than one in a million,

645
71:16.950 --> 71:25.440
or choose whatever r
makes you comfortable. You can't guarantee a correct solution, but you can make the
probability of error negligible

646
71:25.440 --> 71:28.560
for all intents and purposes.

647
71:28.560 --> 71:35.580
Here we are naming these
strings y1 through yk, where we're using superscripts to help us to name these strings,

648
71:35.580 --> 71:40.290
just so that we can reserve subscripts to refer to the individual
bits of those strings.

649
71:40.290 --> 71:47.070
So these aren't exponents
or anything like that, these are just the names that we're giving to these k strings.

650
71:47.070 --> 71:54.390
Each one has length n because we got them
from running the circuit for Simon's algorithm.

651
71:54.390 --> 72:02.940
So we can write down the
individual bits of these k strings like you see right here.

652
72:02.940 --> 72:10.740
What we do now is to create a matrix m, where each entry of this matrix is a bit, and we get these bits from the strings

653
72:10.740 --> 72:14.880
that we just measured, just like as shown right here.

654
72:14.880 --> 72:22.620
So this matrix has k rows and n columns, and its entries are all binary values.

655
72:22.620 --> 72:30.300
Now, we don't know what s is. That's what we're trying to find, but just imagine for a
moment that we did know s,

656
72:30.300 --> 72:36.690
and we formed a column
vector from the bits of s, just like is shown right here.

657
72:36.690 --> 72:43.620
If we were to multiply that vector by m and then take the result modulo-2, or another way of saying that

658
72:43.620 --> 72:51.630
is that we replace addition
with the eXclusive OR, then we will necessarily
get the all-zero vector.

659
72:51.630 --> 72:57.660
That's because each of the
entries in this resulting vector is none other than the
binary dot product of s

660
72:57.660 --> 73:01.050
with one of the rows of m.

661
73:01.050 --> 73:06.960
If S happens to be the all-zero string, we'll always get the zero vector from the binary dot product.

662
73:06.960 --> 73:15.660
And if s is not the all-zero string, we'll get this from what we
know about the probabilities for the strings y1 through yk to appear.

663
73:15.660 --> 73:21.870
In particular, the
binary dot product with s is always zero for all of these strings.

664
73:21.870 --> 73:28.980
A simple way of saying that is that this vector
formed from the bits of s is always in the null
space of the matrix m,

665
73:28.980 --> 73:36.270
assuming that we're doing all
of our arithmetic modulo-2, but of course, we don't know what s is,

666
73:36.270 --> 73:39.630
we're trying to find s.

667
73:39.630 --> 73:46.800
But what we can do is that we can compute the
null space of this matrix m, once again, modulo-2.

668
73:46.800 --> 73:53.070
Specifically, we can do that using the technique of
Gaussian elimination, which is the procedure that's often taught

669
73:53.070 --> 73:56.430
in introductory linear algebra courses.

670
73:56.430 --> 74:04.830
It works perfectly well when we do all of our arithmetic modulo-2, and it can be done quite
efficiently with a computer.

671
74:04.830 --> 74:11.400
And if we compute the null space of m, given the specific way that these k strings have
been randomly chosen,

672
74:11.400 --> 74:18.180
we will be able to recover s with probability greater than
1 minus 2 to the negative r.

673
74:18.180 --> 74:26.310
To be specific, what we will see with probability greater than
1 minus 2 to the negative r is that the null space
includes the all-zero vector,

674
74:26.310 --> 74:34.200
as it always does for every matrix, as well as the vector corresponding to s, whether it's the all-zero vector or not.

675
74:34.200 --> 74:39.630
And most importantly, no other vectors will
appear in the null space.

676
74:39.630 --> 74:43.920
It's actually not too hard to prove this, although I won't go through it in detail.

677
74:43.920 --> 74:53.340
The idea is that if we
have some other string that isn't the all-zero
vector and it isn't s, then each one of the random
strings, y1 through yk,

678
74:53.340 --> 74:58.470
is basically going to knock
it out of the null space with probability a half.

679
74:58.470 --> 75:05.670
So after k shots, it's not
at all likely to survive, and in fact, none of the
strings that don't belong

680
75:05.670 --> 75:14.760
are likely to survive. And a very simple fact
from probability theory, known as the union bound, can
be used to establish that.

681
75:14.760 --> 75:22.710
I haven't explained all
of the details here, but hopefully, you get the idea that by computing the null
space modulo-2 of this matrix m,

682
75:22.710 --> 75:30.630
we are very likely to recover s, and that's how Simon's algorithm
solves Simon's problem.

683
75:30.630 --> 75:38.490
There's just one thing left
to say about Simon's problem, and it concerns the classical
difficulty of this problem,

684
75:38.490 --> 75:45.630
that is, how many queries does a classical query algorithm need to solve Simon's problem?

685
75:45.630 --> 75:49.380
The answer is, a lot, in general.

686
75:49.380 --> 76:00.810
There are different precise
statements that can be made about the classical
difficulty of this problem, and here's just one of them.

687
76:00.810 --> 76:10.110
If we have any probabilistic
query algorithm and that algorithm makes fewer than 2 to the power n over 2
minus 1, minus 1 queries,

688
76:10.110 --> 76:16.680
so that's a number of queries
that's exponential in n, then that algorithm will fail
to solve Simon's problem,

689
76:16.680 --> 76:20.280
with probability at least a half.

690
76:20.280 --> 76:27.090
Sometimes, proving
impossibility results like this can be very challenging, but this one isn't too difficult to prove

691
76:27.090 --> 76:31.260
through an elementary
probabilistic analysis.

692
76:31.260 --> 76:37.920
I won't do that in this video lesson, and I'll just instead focus
on the intuition behind it.

693
76:37.920 --> 76:46.290
We're trying to find the hidden string s, but so long as we don't query the function on two strings having
the same output value,

694
76:46.290 --> 76:50.010
we'll get very limited
information about s.

695
76:50.010 --> 76:59.040
Basically, all we learn is
that the hidden string s is not the eXclusive OR of any two distinct
strings that we've queried,

696
76:59.040 --> 77:05.790
And if we query the function at fewer than this number of queries, there will still be a lot of choices of s

697
77:05.790 --> 77:08.790
that haven't been ruled out.

698
77:08.790 --> 77:13.050
This isn't a formal proof,
but that is the basic idea.

699
77:13.050 --> 77:22.980
So in summary, Simon's algorithm provides us with a striking advantage of quantum over classical
algorithms within the query model.

700
77:22.980 --> 77:32.580
In particular, Simon's
algorithm solves Simon's problem with a number of queries that's linear in the number of input
bits n to our function,

701
77:32.580 --> 77:39.900
whereas any classical algorithm,
even if it's probabilistic, needs to make a number of
queries that's exponential in n

702
77:39.900 --> 77:46.830
in order to solve Simon's problem with a reasonable probability of success.

703
77:46.830 --> 77:54.540
It's true that Simon's problem is a somewhat artificial problem that presumably nobody
really wants to solve,

704
77:54.540 --> 78:01.650
but that's secondary. Sometimes ideas need to be developed before they're put into practice.

705
78:01.650 --> 78:09.030
And indeed, Peter Shor has clearly stated that it was Simon's algorithm that inspired his now
famous quantum algorithm

706
78:09.030 --> 78:14.010
for integer factorization, which we'll see in a couple of lessons.

707
78:14.010 --> 78:17.340
And that is the end of Lesson 5.

708
78:17.340 --> 78:23.370
In this lesson, we've taken a look at the
query model of computation, and we've seen a progression of examples

709
78:23.370 --> 78:30.240
of quantum algorithms
that exhibit advantages over classical algorithms
within this model.

710
78:30.240 --> 78:36.990
There is, in fact, a lot more
known about the query model and quantum algorithms for other problems that
I've not discussed.

711
78:36.990 --> 78:43.320
So if you find this
model to be interesting, there's quite a lot
more to learn about it.

712
78:43.320 --> 78:50.190
Our next step will be to move
away from the query model and toward a model of computation
that's more representative

713
78:50.190 --> 78:55.560
of the sorts of problems that we might hope to solve in practice.

714
78:55.560 --> 79:03.060
I hope you'll join me for Lesson 6, where will focus mainly on
laying down a foundation for studying quantum algorithms.

715
79:03.060 --> 79:09.630
And from there, we'll move on to some
specific quantum algorithms, including Shor's algorithm
for integer factorization

716
79:09.630 --> 79:12.663
in subsequent lessons. Goodbye until then!
